<h4>How long will raw milk last?</h4>

<p>You should have no problems with getting your milk to last the two weeks. It helps to keep the lid screwed on tightly and keep it in the part of your fridge least affected by temperature fluctuations. You may have to experiment a bit with the temperature of your fridge. However, once it's opened, generally it has about a week before it starts to sour. </p>

<p>One difference between pasteurized and raw milk is that pasteurized milk goes bad, and raw milk sours naturally. So even if it starts to smell a little funny, it's just beginning a stage of fermentation, and according to the Weston A. Price Foundation, it's still safe to drink. You could also use it to cook with, or make yogurt or other cultured dairy products if it sours beyond what your taste buds can handle. Or, you can freeze what you aren't using. Freezing can change the texture of the milk, as the cream doesn't mix as easily into the milk once it's been frozen. But it still tastes fine.</p>


