<h4>What is the difference between pasture-raised meat and organic meat that I can buy at my local grocery store?</h4>

<p>Just because meat is labeled "organic" does not mean that itâ€™s very good for you, or that the animals are treated well. To be certified organic, the requirements are that the animals be hormone and anti-biotic free, and that their feed be organic. It is not required that they spend adequate time outside. In fact, many animals who are raised "organically" may not see any sunshine at all.</p>

<p>Pasture-raised animals have plenty of access to the outdoors, and spend much of their time there. At Hopeful Farms, we believe that being "organic" isn't enough. Our animals are raised on pasture, eating greens and soaking in the sunshine. Since our animals are fed a natural diet, they don't need medications. </p>

<p>Our biggest focus is on our littlest livestock, the microbial life in our soil. Animals can only be as healthy as the plants they consume, and the plants they consume can only be as healthy as the soil they grow on. At Fry Farms, we put emphasis on taking care of the soil. Applying the correct balance of minerals to enhance the microbial life is one step in doing that. Microbes, in return, work for us by helping the plants absorb nutrients. No herbicides, insecticides or chemical fertilizers are used since they kill the life in the soil.</p>


